Ahh okay Deepa — I see exactly what’s happening here 👀
This is not a big issue, just a small Git + Windows command detail.

🧠 Why you are getting this error
fatal: pathspec '...' did not match any files

👉 Means:

Git cannot find that file in tracking (index)
🔍 Possible reasons (one of these is true)
✅ 1. File is NOT added to Git yet

👉 If file was never committed:

git rm --cached ❌ won’t work

👉 Because Git is not tracking it

✅ 2. File name has spaces (VERY IMPORTANT ⚠️)

You typed:

git rm --cached Git commands.txt

👉 Git reads it as:

Git   ❌
commands.txt ❌
✅ FIX (correct command)

Use quotes:

git rm --cached "Git commands.txt"
✅ 3. File path is wrong

Maybe file is inside folder like:

notes/Git commands.txt

Then use:

git rm --cached "notes/Git commands.txt"
✅ 4. File is already ignored

If .gitignore already has:

*.txt

👉 And file was never committed:

Nothing to remove ✅

👉 So error is actually OK 👍

🧪 Let’s verify (DO THIS)

Run:

git status
👉 Check output:
Case 1:
nothing to commit

👉 ✅ You're safe — files are not tracked

Case 2:
tracked files listed

👉 Then we fix using correct path

💡 Best way (simple for you)

Since you're using IntelliJ:

👉 Do this instead (easier than terminal):

Go to file
Right-click
Click:
Git → Add to .gitignore

DONE ✅

🎯 Final understanding
Situation	What happens
File never committed	❌ rm --cached not needed
File committed	✅ use rm --cached
File has spaces	✅ use quotes
